\section{Implementation Details}
\label{sec:impl}

This section describes the concrete realization of Multimodal Contextual Reasoning (MCR) that instantiates the rollout dynamics in Eqs.~\eqref{eq:mcr_main}--\eqref{eq:mcr_context}, including the tool interface (\(\pi\)), perception update (\(\delta\)), action update (\(\rho\)), context aggregation (\(\oplus\)), and training hyperparameters.

\subsection{Tooling and Environment Interface}
\label{sec:impl_tools}

We implement tool use through an external executor \(\pi(\cdot)\) which receives a structured action \(\mathbf{A}_i\) and returns a structured feedback object \(\mathbf{F}_{i+1}\).
Each tool call follows a unified schema
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:tool_schema}
\mathbf{A}_i = \langle \texttt{name}, \texttt{args} \rangle
\quad\mapsto\quad
\mathbf{F}_{i+1} = \pi(\mathbf{A}_i)\in\mathcal{J},
\end{equation}
where \(\mathcal{J}\) denotes a JSON-serializable space containing (i) execution \texttt{status}, (ii) an optional \texttt{error} field, and (iii) a payload (text, timestamps, bounding boxes, etc.). Failed calls return \texttt{status=error} and a short diagnostic message; the policy may retry or switch tools at the next step.

\paragraph{Enabled tools.}
We enable a benchmark-dependent subset from the following tool families.

\noindent\textbf{Video tools.}
\texttt{video.sample(start,end,fps,max\_frames)} returns uniformly sampled RGB frames with timestamps.
\texttt{video.asr(start,end)} returns timestamped transcript segments (or cached full-video ASR).
\texttt{video.retrieve(query,topk)} retrieves relevant transcript chunks and returns \((t_{\mathrm{start}},t_{\mathrm{end}},\text{text})\) tuples.

\noindent\textbf{Document tools.}
\texttt{doc.retrieve(query,topk)} returns relevant chunks with document/page offsets (dense + lexical fusion).
\texttt{doc.ocr(page\_range)} runs OCR and returns normalized text with line-level bounding boxes.
\texttt{doc.open(page)} returns a rendered page image (optionally cropped).

\noindent\textbf{General tools.}
\texttt{code.exec(python)} executes Python in a sandbox and returns stdout/stderr for verification.
\texttt{memory.write/read} provides explicit key-value memory (mainly for agent tasks).
\texttt{terminate(final\_answer)} ends the rollout.

Tool outputs are appended to the shared context \(\mathbf{C}\) as serialized records (tool name, arguments, status, and truncated payload).

\subsection{Rollout Loop and Structured Outputs}
\label{sec:impl_rollout}

We implement MCR as an explicit closed-loop rollout with a maximum step budget \(N_{\max}\).
At each step \(i\), the policy \(f_\theta\) produces an intermediate result \(\mathbf{R}_i\) from the task \(\mathbf{Q}\), current perception \(\mathbf{V}_i\), prior actions \(\mathbf{A}_i\), feedback \(\mathbf{F}_i\), and accumulated context \(\mathbf{C}_i\):
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:impl_policy}
\mathbf{R}_i \sim f_{\theta}\!\left(\mathbf{Q}\mid \mathbf{V}_i,\mathbf{A}_i,\mathbf{F}_i,\mathbf{C}_i\right).
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Structured action format.}
To make \(\pi\) executable and enable trajectory supervision, we constrain the assistant to output a machine-parseable JSON object with either:
\begin{align}
\label{eq:impl_action_mode}
\textbf{Action mode:}\quad
\mathbf{R}_i &= \{\texttt{plan},\ \texttt{action}=\langle \texttt{name},\texttt{args}\rangle,\ \texttt{final}=\varnothing\},\\
\label{eq:impl_terminate_mode}
\textbf{Terminate mode:}\quad
\mathbf{R}_i &= \{\texttt{final}=\text{answer string}\}.
\end{align}
In action mode, we parse \(\texttt{action}\) into \(\mathbf{A}_i\) and execute it in the environment:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:impl_execute}
\mathbf{F}_{i+1} \sim \pi(\mathbf{A}_i \mid \mathbf{R}_i,\mathbf{Q}).
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Perception update \(\delta\).}
The next perception \(\mathbf{V}_{i+1}\) is determined by an evidence-selection policy:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:impl_delta}
\mathbf{V}_{i+1} \sim \delta(\mathbf{V}_i \mid \mathbf{R}_i,\mathbf{F}_{i+1}),
\end{equation}
where \(\delta\) is implemented as: (i) an explicit window request produced by the model (e.g., a temporal range, page range, or crop), and (ii) a deterministic fallback when omitted (\(\mathbf{V}_{i+1}=\mathbf{V}_i\)). For videos, \(\delta\) loads only frames within the requested window; for documents, it loads retrieved chunks and/or page images.

\paragraph{Action update \(\rho\).}
In practice, \(\rho\) is absorbed into the policy output: the next tool call is specified in \(\mathbf{R}_i\) and becomes \(\mathbf{A}_i\) after parsing. This is consistent with
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:impl_rho}
\mathbf{A}_{i+1} \sim \rho(\mathbf{A}_i \mid \mathbf{R}_i,\mathbf{F}_{i+1},\mathbf{Q}).
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Context aggregation \(\oplus\).}
After each step, we aggregate the trace into the shared context:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:impl_context_append}
\mathbf{C}_{i+1} = \mathbf{C}_i \oplus \left(\mathbf{R}_i,\mathbf{A}_i,\mathbf{F}_{i+1}\right),
\quad \mathbf{C}_1=\mathbf{T}_{\texttt{sys}}.
\end{equation}
The rollout terminates if \(\mathbf{R}_i\) contains \texttt{final} (i.e., \(\mathbf{R}_N \models \mathbf{Q}\)) or if \(i=N_{\max}\).

\subsection{Context Construction and Compression}
\label{sec:impl_compress}

Long-horizon rollouts can exceed the model context limit. We implement a two-tier memory with (i) a verbatim \emph{recent window} and (ii) a compressed \emph{memory block} for older steps.

\paragraph{Two-tier buffer.}
We keep the most recent \(k\) steps in full fidelity, and summarize earlier interactions into a structured memory block that is prepended to the context. Compression is triggered when the prompt length exceeds a budget \(B\) (typically \(0.85\text{--}0.90\) of the maximum context length). The memory block includes: solved/unsolved subgoals, key evidence with citations (timestamps/pages), tool results that must persist (IDs, retrieved chunk references), and an updated plan.

\paragraph{Payload truncation and re-fetching.}
To reduce context usage, long tool payloads (e.g., transcripts) are truncated and replaced with (i) short excerpts, (ii) citations/IDs, and (iii) a handle that allows re-fetching via tools in later steps. This preserves the semantics of \(\oplus\) in Eq.~\eqref{eq:impl_context_append} while keeping prompts within budget.

\subsection{Evidence Representation}
\label{sec:impl_evidence}

\paragraph{Video.}
\(\mathbf{V}_i\) contains a set of frames with timestamps and (optionally) a transcript window. The initial evidence \(\mathbf{V}_{\texttt{init}}\) uses coarse uniform sampling over the full duration. Subsequent steps use \(\delta\) to zoom in temporally and resample at a higher FPS.

\paragraph{Documents.}
\(\mathbf{V}_i\) contains retrieved text chunks and optionally rendered page images. OCR results are returned as tool feedback \(\mathbf{F}\) and only the most relevant lines (bounded by a token cap) are injected back into the prompt.

\subsection{Training Procedure}
\label{sec:impl_training}

\paragraph{Supervised fine-tuning (SFT).}
We train \(f_\theta\) on MCR trajectories with teacher forcing. Each training instance consists of the context and evidence \((\mathbf{C}_i,\mathbf{V}_i,\mathbf{A}_i,\mathbf{F}_i)\) as input and the next assistant JSON \(\mathbf{R}_i\) as the target. We optimize token-level cross-entropy on assistant turns only; tool outputs are included as inputs but are not predicted.

\paragraph{Optional RL and preference optimization.}
When enabled, we perform rollout-based optimization with an automatic verifier and a step/tool-cost shaped reward, followed by a small amount of preference optimization (e.g., DPO/IPO) using sampled rollout pairs ranked by correctness, grounding, and efficiency.

\subsection{Hyperparameters}
\label{sec:impl_hparams}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{6pt}
\begin{tabular}{l l}
\hline
\textbf{Component} & \textbf{Setting} \\
\hline
Max rollout steps \(N_{\max}\) & 8 (short video QA), 12 (long video/doc), 20 (agent) \\
Tool calls per step & 1 (default) \\
Keep-last steps \(k\) (verbatim) & 4 \\
Compression trigger & prompt length \(>0.85\text{--}0.90\times\) context limit \\
Memory block target length & 300--800 tokens \\
Tool payload truncation & excerpt + citation/ID + re-fetch handle \\
\hline
Initial video sampling & 0.5--1 FPS, max 64 frames \\
Zoom-in video sampling & 2--4 FPS, max 32 frames/step \\
ASR chunk length & 10--20s (overlap 2--5s) \\
Transcript retrieval top-\(k\) & 5 \\
\hline
Doc chunk size & 512--1024 tokens (10--20\% overlap) \\
Doc retrieval top-\(k\) & 5 (up to 10) \\
OCR injection budget & top lines, typically \(\le\)1--2k tokens \\
\hline
Optimizer (SFT) & AdamW \\
Learning rate & \(2\times 10^{-5}\) (range \(1\text{e-}5\) to \(5\text{e-}5\)) \\
Weight decay & 0.05 \\
Warmup ratio & 0.03 \\
Global batch size & 256--1024 (via grad accumulation) \\
Epochs & 1--3 \\
\hline
RL reward (optional) &
\( \mathbb{1}[\text{success}] - \alpha\cdot \text{steps} - \beta\cdot \text{tool\_calls} - \gamma\cdot \mathbb{1}[\text{tool\_error}] \) \\
\(\alpha,\beta,\gamma\) (optional) & \(\alpha\in[0.005,0.02],\ \beta\in[0.01,0.05],\ \gamma\in[0.1,0.3]\) \\
DPO temperature \(\beta\) (optional) & 0.1--0.3 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\vspace{2pt}
\caption{Default hyperparameters for MCR rollouts, context compression, and training. Values are kept fixed across benchmarks unless otherwise stated.}
\label{tab:impl_hparams}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Practical reproducibility details.}
We enforce JSON validity for \(\mathbf{R}_i\) using either grammar-constrained decoding or strict post-hoc validation with re-decoding. Tool calls are cached by argument hash (e.g., video window and FPS) to reduce variance and improve throughput. Each rollout logs \((\mathbf{Q},\{\mathbf{V}_i,\mathbf{R}_i,\mathbf{A}_i,\mathbf{F}_{i+1}\}_{i=1}^{N})\) for replay and offline filtering.
